tspan.tspan: Zapf in 1948, shortly after World War II, and immediately enjoyed
widespread popularity. It is named after the Italian caligrapher Giambattista
Palatino. A classical serif typeface, evoking a strong, open style that’s highly
legible. The weight of the typeface is thicker than a normal roman in order to
increase the legibility. The Palatino typeface family is said to be one of the
top ten most-used typefaces in the, world. This typeface is based on the
humanist types of the Italian Renaissance, which mirror the letters formed
by a broad nib pen, evoking Zapf's expertise as a calligrapher.
